#X text 219 39 Modes;
#X text 47 221 When there are 2 dimensions in the default mode 0 \, then a click on any of the opposit axis lines will move the filled square to that line while remaining on the first.;
#X text 199 296 single (1);
#X text 196 143 default (0);
#X text 192 441 multiple (2);
#X text 48 164 The "default" mode allows only one filled square per line. This follows the original radio behavior of the single-dimensional radio.;
#X text 50 324 The "single" mode allows only one filled square \, like before \, but this time it can freely move to any cell. If this is a single-dimensional radio \, it behaves as the default mode. However \, if there are 2 dimensions \, then the filled square can jump anywhere.;
#X obj 517 545 s radio-test;
#X msg 517 465 resize 2 3 \, mode 2;
#X obj 524 491 tgl 20 0 empty empty empty 0 -10 0 12 #fcfcfc #000000 #000000 0 1;
#X msg 524 516 orientation \$1;
#X text 46 469 The "multiple" mode only works on two-dimensional matrices \, and allows for as many filled squares as the opposite axis to the orientation can hold. In a (2 \, 3) matrix with 2 columns and 3 rows \, a horizontal mode allows for 3 filled squares (3 rows) \, but a vertical mode allows for 2 filled squares (2 columns).;
#X text 193 596 disable (-1);
